result.execSummary:
The defendant Dale D. Honkala was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Possess/Illegally Obtained Prescription, an unclassified misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 450.11(7)(h).

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

miscConds.notes:
The defendant must maintain/obtain full time employment/school that consists of at least 35 hrs/week.

When not full time employed/school, the defendant must apply for at least 3 jobs per week and report progress monthly to P&P with pertinent information in regards to applications.  The defendant must only apply for jobs qualified for - must accept any job offered - must not engage in any conduct that could result in the termination of his/her employment/school.
No consumption or possession of alcohol and no entry into any bars or taverns.
The defendant must undergo an AODA assessment and follow thru with all recommendations.

records.addlTxt: Email from atty Lynch to DA re: sentencing

Defendant Dale D. Honkala in court with attorney Chad Lynch.  Defendant Dale D. Honkala in custody.  Charles James Simono appeared for the State of Wisconsin. Called 17CF03 & 16CF61 Called 10:48 am. 17CF03 here for change of plea &  sentencing and 16CF61 here on sentencing  on revocation.  17CF03 offer: plead to count 1 and DRI count 2 - 39 months  WPS - 15 months in and 24 months extended supervision conditions will be up to probation at the time of release and agrees to programming if available to him.  On 16CF61 time served joint recommendation. All parties have revocation paperwork - Lynch one error and indicates what it is DE doesn't believe he was arrested on warrant. State makes argument on 16CF61 112 days credit (stipulated) time served. Lynch and Honkala agree and withholds comment. Court sentences the defendant to time served on count 1 - 112 days any unpaid fines turned into civil judgment. On 17CF03 court DRI count 2 and DE pleads G to count 1 as alleged. DE acknowledges that he understands what DRI means.  Court goes over plea questionnaire and finds DE is entering his plea freely, voluntarily and intelligently. Factual basis exists. Accepts plea and adjudges G of count 1 as alleged. Proceed to sentencing. State recites joint recommendation - count 1 - 39 months WPS with 15 months imposed and 24 months on extended supervision. P&P to determine conditions for extended supervision. Lynch makes statement follow joint recommendation. Honkala withholds comment. Court sentences to the following: Count 1 - 39 months WPS with 15 months initial incarceration and 24 months on extended supervision with P&P to determine conditions. Eligible for programming. Costs. DNA rights given - no possession of firearms - voting rights given - appeal rights given. Costs to be paid out of prison funds.
Sentencing hearing on revocation on October 12, 2017 at 10:30 am.

Defendant Dale D. Honkala in court with attorney John E Voorhees.  Charles James Simono appeared for the State of Wisconsin. Called at 11:04 AM. State - resolved - amend only count to 450.11(7)(h), possessing a prescription without a valid prescription - unclassified misd, 1 year probation with conditions of: $100.00 fine plus costs, AODA, no possession of any controlled substances and no entry into any taverns or bars, employment/school. Voorhees and Honkala agree. Court amends only count to possession of a prescription drug without a valid prescription contrary to 450.11(7)(h) - reads new charge and penalty. Honkala pleads G to count #1 as amended. Court has plea questionnaire, goes thru it, finds the defendant has freely, voluntarily and intelligently waived his constitutional rights by entering his plea and right to JT, accepts plea, adjudges guilty, proceed to sentencing. State makes final argument prior to sentencing - follow joint recommendation. Voorhees makes final argument prior to sentencing - follow joint recommendation. Honkala withholds comment. Court sentences the defendant to the following: withhold sentence and place on probation for 1 year with conditions of: $100.00 fine plus costs - paid thru probation, AODA and follow thru, no possession of consumption of alcohol and no entry into any bars or taverns, maintain/obtain full time employment/school, 50 hours of community service, submit DNA sample with expunction rights given, credit for 7 days only if revoked (stipulated), right to appeal, adjourned.
Final pre-trial on April 27, 2016 at 10:45 am.

Defendant Dale D. Honkala in court with attorney John E Voorhees.  Charles James Simono appeared for the State of Wisconsin. Called at 2:20 PM. State - offers have been made to the defendant to get him to waive his PH today. Voorhees and Honkala agree, Voorhees provides court with waiver of PH form. Court goes thru it, finds the defendant has freely, voluntarily and intelligently waived his right to PH, finds probable cause, binds over for trial. State has filed an Information that mirrors the complaint. Voorhees has Information, waives reading of it, will proceed to ARGN, pleads NG to all counts. Court accepts pleas, continues bond, sets for FPT.  Final pre-trial scheduled for April 27, 2016 at 10:45 am.
Preliminary hearing on March 30, 2016 at 01:45 pm.

Attorney John E Voorhees in court.  Charles James Simono appeared for the State of Wisconsin. No other appearances. Called 2:23 PM. State - here for PH. Voorhees unaware of where client is and had anticipated waiving the PH. Court will move matter to the end of the day to be re-called if the the defendant appears. Adjourned, 2:25PM. Never called back on the record - per court - Clerk re-scheduled.  Preliminary hearing scheduled for March 30, 2016 at 01:45 pm.
